{"cursor":"48761","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n ]] A 'motorcycle' (also called a 'motorbike', 'bike', 'moto' or 'cycle') is a\n two {{cite book\n| title = Motorcycle Handling and Chassis Design pages = 4â1 last = Foale first\n| = Tony publisher = Tony Foale Designs year = 2006 isbn = 978-84-933286-3-\n| 4}} or three wheeled {{cite book title = Motorcycle Dynamics last =\n| Cossalter first = Vittore publisher = Lulu year = 2006 isbn = 978-1-4303-0861-\n| 4}} motor vehicle. Motorcycles vary considerably depending on the task\n| they are designed for, such as long distance travel, navigating congested\n| urban traffic, cruising, sport and racing, or off-road conditions.\n\nMotorcycles are one of the most affordable forms of motorised transport in\nmany parts of the world and, for most of the world's population, they are also\nthe most common type of motor vehicle. There are around 200 million motorcycles\n(including mopeds, motor scooters, motorised bicycles, and other powered two\nand three-wheelers) in use worldwide, {{Cite journal |title=Fuel Cell\nPowered Motorcycles |first=Adachi |last=Shuhei(Yamaha Motor Co., Ltd., JPN)\n|journal=Journal of the Society of Automotive Engineers of Japan |issn=0385-\n7298 |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=90â93 |year=2006 |url=http://sciencelinks.jp/j-\neast/article/200603/000020060306A0040069.php }} or about 33 motorcycles\nper 1000 people. This compares to around 590 million cars, or about 91 per\n1000 people.\n\nMost of the motorcycles, 58%, are in the developing countries of Asia Southern\nand Eastern Asia, and the Asia Pacific countries, excluding Japan while 33% of\nthe cars (195 million) are concentrated in the United States and Japan. In 2006,\nChina had 54 million motorcycles in use and an annual production of 22 million\nunits. [http://www.webbikeworld.com/motorcycle-news/statistics/2008-japan-\nmotorcycle-\nstatistics.htm] [http://www.caam.org.cn/MotorCycleStatistics/20101118-\n/0905048503.html] , India, with an estimated 37 million\nmotorcycles/mopeds, was home to the largest number of motorised two wheelers in\nthe world. China came a close second with 34 million motorcycles/mopeds. {{Cite web |title=Passenger Cars; Map No. 31\n|work=Worldmapper: The world as you've never seen it before |year=2002\n|url=http://www.sasi.group.shef.ac.uk/worldmapper/display.php?selected=31 }} See\n[http://www.sasi.group.shef.ac.uk/worldmapper/display.php?selected=31# Technical\nnotes for this data] See\n[http://www.sasi.group.shef.ac.uk/worldmapper/display.php?selected=32# data\nfiles for the statistics]\n","linknr":866,"url":"Motorcycle","recorded":1362477305,"links":117,"instances":["engine","motorcycle","australia","motorcycle","road_usage","motorcycle"],"pdf":["http://socrates.berkeley.edu/~fajans/pub/pdffiles/SteerBikeAJP.PDF","http://socrates.berkeley.edu/~fajans/pub/pdffiles/SteerBikeAJP.PDF","http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/pubs/811159.pdf","http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/pubs/811159.pdf","http://msf-usa.org/downloads/If_you_ride_a_motorcycle.pdf","http://msf-usa.org/downloads/If_you_ride_a_motorcycle.pdf","http://www.msf-usa.org/imsc/proceedings/b-Smith-ThreeDimensionalAnalysisofRiderPosture.pdf","http://www.msf-usa.org/imsc/proceedings/b-Smith-ThreeDimensionalAnalysisofRiderPosture.pdf","http://www.vespausa.com/wwh/Vespanomics-platform.pdf","http://www.vespausa.com/wwh/Vespanomics-platform.pdf"],"categories":["1885 introductions","Articles with inconsistent citation formats","Motorcycle technology|","Motorcycles|","Motorcycling","Wheeled vehicles"],"headings":["History","Demographics","Use","Technical aspects","Safety","Types","Motorcycle rider postures","Legal definitions and restrictions","Environmental impact","See also","References","External links",""],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Triumph_T_110_650_cc_1954.jpg/300px-Triumph_T_110_650_cc_1954.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.